    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>How is GPA calculated on a 4.0 scale?</summary>
          <p>Each letter grade is assigned a numeric value: A = 4.0, B = 3.0, C = 2.0, D = 1.0, F = 0.0, with plus/minus grades adjusting by 0.3. Multiply each grade's point value by the course's credit hours to get quality points, sum all quality points, and divide by total credit hours. Use our <a href="/math-calculators/gpa-calculator/">GPA calculator</a> to compute yours instantly.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>What is the difference between weighted and unweighted GPA?</summary>
          <p>An unweighted GPA uses the standard 4.0 scale for all courses regardless of difficulty. A weighted GPA adds extra points for advanced courses: typically 0.5 for honors classes (making an A worth 4.5) and 1.0 for AP or IB classes (making an A worth 5.0). This rewards students who take more challenging coursework by reflecting the additional difficulty in their GPA.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Do colleges prefer weighted or unweighted GPA?</summary>
          <p>Most selective colleges look at both but often recalculate GPAs using their own system. They evaluate your unweighted GPA to see your raw grade performance and examine your course rigor separately. A slightly lower GPA with challenging courses is generally viewed more favorably than a perfect GPA with only easy courses. Many admissions offices rate "rigor of secondary school record" as one of the most important factors.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>What is a good GPA?</summary>
          <p>A 3.0 (B average) is generally considered good and meets minimum requirements for many programs and scholarships. A 3.5 or above is strong and competitive for selective colleges. A 3.7 or higher is excellent. The national average high school GPA is approximately 3.0. For highly selective universities, admitted students typically have unweighted GPAs of 3.8 to 4.0. Context matters: a 3.5 with rigorous courses is often valued more than a 4.0 with easy ones.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Can I raise my GPA in one semester?</summary>
          <p>Yes, but the impact depends on how many credit hours you have already completed. With 30 existing credit hours, earning a 4.0 in a 15-credit semester can raise your GPA by 0.3 to 0.5 points. With 90 credit hours, the same performance produces a smaller increase. Focus on your highest-credit courses for maximum impact, use your school's grade replacement policy if available, and use our <a href="/math-calculators/gpa-calculator/">GPA calculator</a> to model what grades you need.</p>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

